# Cross-Project Memory Index

Memories that apply across every project on this machine. Project-specific
memories live in `~/.claude/projects/{slug}/memory/` and follow the same
format.

## Where memories go

Each memory is a short Markdown file with `name` / `description` / `type`
frontmatter, filed under a directory by subject:

- `tools/{name}.md` — external systems, CLIs, vaults, services.
- `domain/{topic}/` — knowledge about a product, codebase, or area that
  spans sessions (a staging area — promote to a skill/plugin as it matures).
- `general.md` — cross-cutting workflow/writing preferences.
- top level — identity and persistent personal preferences.

`type` tells Claude *how to apply* the memory:

- **user** — explicitly stated, stable facts/preferences about the human.
- **feedback** — lessons from corrections or observed dissatisfaction; apply
  as a behavioural adjustment.
- **project** — current or repo-specific working context, decisions, in-flight
  state.
- **reference** — durable pointers to external systems, docs, services,
  accounts.

**Directory and `type` should agree — move a memory, don't mislabel it.** If it
came from a correction, prefer `feedback` over `user`; if it's a durable
external pointer rather than current project state, prefer `reference` over
`project`. A global-memory file that's really about one project belongs in
per-project memory (`~/.claude/projects/<slug>/memory/`) — promote or demote it.
The worked pairings table and examples live in this repo's `README.md`.

## Authoring conventions

Entries follow the per-project memory format the harness defines, frontmatter
included — `type` nested under `metadata:`; `[[name]]` links target a memory's
`name:` field; `feedback`/`project` bodies carry `Why:` / `How to apply:` lines;
dates absolute. This layer differs in just one way: related gotchas group per
`tools/{name}.md` rather than one file per fact — and conversely, a file that
has accreted unrelated subjects should be split back into per-subject files.
Keep `name:` short and slug-like so `[[name]]` link targets stay clean.

## Index-line salience (the lazy-load escape hatch)

Entry bodies load **lazily** — only when one looks relevant to the task.
The index (this file) is injected *mechanically*: the memory-loader hook
(installed by the bootstrap) emits the `## Entries` section into every
main session at start/resume/clear/compact and into every non-lean
subagent at spawn — the same load guarantee the per-project layer gets.
So the one-line entry is guaranteed to be in context when you act; that
guarantee is what makes promoting a line worthwhile. The failure mode
that remains: a gotcha that matters at *command-formation time* whose
body wasn't judged relevant and pulled, so the command fails first —
reactive, not proactive.

For most entries a descriptive pointer is fine; keep the long tail terse.
But for the few gotchas that are both **frequent** and **costly**
(especially ones that fail *silently* or are deterministic and
tool-input-shaped), make the index line **lead with the imperative rule**,
not a topic label — the always-loaded line then doubles as an always-on
reminder, at no extra load. For example:
`[Git Bash — interactive aliases no-op](tools/git-bash.md) — **use
\cp/\rm/\mv when overwriting/deleting** — plain cp/rm/mv reports success
but does nothing non-interactively`.

Reserve this for the handful that clear *both* bars; over-promoting bloats
the index and erodes routing quality (see the cost note in the README) —
and the loader injects into every non-lean subagent too, so bloat
multiplies under fan-out (it warns past ~200 entry lines). On a machine
without the hook, the global CLAUDE.md carries one fallback line: read
this file before proceeding. When a rule is destructive *and*
mechanically matchable, a `PreToolUse` guardrail hook is the heavier
action-point mechanism — for *when* that's justified over an index line
and how to add one, see `HOOKS.md`.

## Maintenance

Two skills keep the store healthy; both no-op on a small set and pay off
after ~10+ entries or a few months:

- **`memory-sweep`** (bundled here; install with `bootstrap --install-skills`)
  — the periodic cross-store sweep over **every** memory store (all per-project
  dirs + this one). The only tool that proposes **promotions**: per-project
  facts that have proven useful across projects, moved up here. It *delegates*
  the per-directory deep clean to `consolidate-memory` rather than reimplementing it.
- **`anthropic-skills:consolidate-memory`** — the deep pass over a *single*
  directory (merge duplicates, prune stale facts, fix orphan links);
  `memory-sweep` calls it. It does not span stores or promote.

